"An arcade cabinet without an attract mode is a cabinet nobody
walks up to. When the machine is idle, a recording of the game
plays. The passer-by sees action, imagines themselves playing, drops
in a coin.

Motoi Scheme exposes tape recording and playback:

- `world/tape-record! tape-id` — start recording input to tape-id
- `world/tape-save tape-id path` — save the tape to persistent storage
- `world/tape-replay tape-id-or-path` — play the tape back
- `world/tape-stop! tape-id` — stop recording
- `world/tape-frames tape-id` — get length of recording
- `world/tape-hash tape-id` — checksum for determinism

This appendix wires tapes into an attract mode.

## Basic recording

Start a game, record inputs, save.

```scheme
(define (record-play-session)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/tape-record! 'demo)
  ;; ... your game runs, inputs are captured ...
  (world/spawn 'player 160 210)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (when (input/down? 'left) ...)
     (when (input/down? 'right) ...)
     ;; ... game logic ...
     )))

;; When done:
(world/tape-stop! 'demo)
(world/tape-save 'demo 'saved-demo)
```

Every input during recording is captured. The tape stores WHAT WAS
PRESSED WHEN, not the resulting game state.

## Playback

```scheme
(define (attract-mode)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/spawn 'player 160 210)
  ;; Same setup as recorded game.
  (world/tape-replay 'saved-demo)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     ;; The tape drives input automatically.
     (world/step)
     (paint-clear)
     (world/each 'player
                 (lambda (p)
                   (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8))))))
```

During replay, `input/down?` and `input/pressed?` return the
recorded values instead of live inputs. Same game, same outcomes,
no player needed.

## Wiring into the cabinet

Chapter 14's cabinet had attract → title → play → game-over →
attract. Now populate attract with tape playback.

```scheme
(define game-state 'attract)
(define state-timer 0)

(define (transition new-state)
  (set! game-state new-state)
  (set! state-timer 0)
  (case new-state
    ((attract)
     (world/reset!)
     (world/tape-replay 'saved-demo))
    ((play)
     (world/reset!)
     (world/tape-record! 'current-play)
     (init-play))))

(define (game-frame)
  (set! state-timer (+ state-timer 1))
  (case game-state
    ((attract)
     ;; Watch the demo. Real-player button press interrupts.
     (game-step-and-paint)
     (when (input/pressed? 'a)     ;; Real player input
       (transition 'play)))
    ((play)
     (game-step-and-paint)
     (when (game-over?)
       (world/tape-stop! 'current-play)
       ;; Optionally: overwrite the demo with this session if score > threshold.
       (when (> current-score demo-threshold)
         (world/tape-save 'current-play 'saved-demo))
       (transition 'game-over)))
    ((game-over)
     (paint-game-over-screen)
     (when (> state-timer 180) (transition 'attract)))))
```

**Nice property:** the attract-mode demo automatically UPGRADES over
time. Every session that scores higher than the previous demo
replaces it. Kids see progressively better demos. The machine
learns to advertise itself.

## Determinism concerns

Tape replay works cleanly only if game outcomes are DETERMINISTIC —
same inputs, same seed → same result. Sources of nondeterminism:

- `world/hash` returns a pseudo-random each call. Seed it at level
  start with the tape's own seed so replay reproduces.
- Frame timing variance in the runtime. Usually the runtime
  handles this — replay locks to logical-frame count, not
  wallclock.
- Cortex writes to persistent storage. If a demo writes, on replay
  it writes again. Guard writes with a `(replay?)` predicate.

## Handling nondeterminism

```scheme
(define (replay-active?)
  (world/tape-frames 'saved-demo) 0)  ; > 0 if replay in progress

(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (unless (replay-active?)
    (cortex/write 'session-score current-score)))
```

Only write during live play, not during replay.

## Verifying deterministic replay

`world/tape-hash` returns a checksum of world state at each frame.
Compare across runs.

```scheme
(define (checksum-after-frames n)
  (let loop ((i 0))
    (when (< i n) (world/step) (loop (+ i 1))))
  (world/tape-hash 'current-play))

;; Record.
(world/tape-record! 'test)
(let ((hash1 (checksum-after-frames 60)))
  (world/tape-stop! 'test)
  (world/tape-save 'test 'saved)
  ;; Replay.
  (world/reset!)
  (world/tape-replay 'saved)
  (let ((hash2 (checksum-after-frames 60)))
    (if (equal? hash1 hash2)
        (display \"Determinism OK\")
        (display \"Determinism BROKEN\"))))
```

Fails? Find the nondeterministic call and seed it.

## Two-tape shuffle

Store two demos and alternate between them for variety.

```scheme
(define demo-index 0)
(define demos '(saved-demo-1 saved-demo-2))

(define (start-attract)
  (world/tape-replay (list-ref demos demo-index))
  (set! demo-index (modulo (+ demo-index 1) (length demos))))
```

Every attract cycle, next demo. Passers-by see fresh action.

## Common desktop tasks

**Shop tour recorder.** A shop can record its owner's 'ideal tour'
of the product catalog. New visitors see an auto-tour on landing.
Same tape mechanism.

**Onboarding replay.** A new user's first session is recorded. They
can replay it later to see their own progress.

**Bug-report tapes.** When a user reports a bug, ask them to
record the session. The tape reproduces the exact issue for the
developer. Better than 'it happened once, I can't remember what I
did.'

## Pitfalls

**Tape includes real-life pauses.** If the recording paused for
tea, the replay pauses for tea. Use tape-editing (not always
exposed by runtime) or record shorter sessions.

**Replay diverges after N seconds.** Nondeterminism sneaked in.
Debug with `world/tape-hash` checkpoints.

**Tape file huge.** Long sessions can produce large tapes. Cap
recording at 60 seconds for attract mode. Or record only
'interesting' segments.

**Real-player input during replay.** Chapter 14 handles this:
`input/pressed? 'a` from a REAL player interrupts and transitions
to 'play. Otherwise you'd have both replayed and live inputs
fighting each other.

## The 30-second attract loop

Cabinet defaults:

```scheme
(define attract-max-frames (* 60 30))  ; 30 seconds

((eq? game-state 'attract)
 (game-step-and-paint)
 (when (or (input/pressed? 'a) (> state-timer attract-max-frames))
   (if (input/pressed? 'a) (transition 'play) (transition 'title))))
```

30 seconds is the sweet spot: long enough to convey the game,
short enough that a bored bystander sees the loop restart. Then
title screen for 5 seconds. Then attract again.

## Legendary tapes

If you record a player crushing your game (say, 100k+ score), save
that tape as a 'legendary demo' and play it occasionally. Kids
LOVE seeing extraordinary play. Motivates them to try harder.

Save with:
```scheme
(when (> current-score 100000)
  (world/tape-save 'current-play (string->symbol
                                  (string-append \"legend-\"
                                                 (number->string current-score)))))
```

Load a random legendary demo:
```scheme
(let ((legend-tapes (cortex/read 'legend-tapes)))
  (when (pair? legend-tapes)
    (world/tape-replay (list-ref legend-tapes
                                 (modulo (world/hash) (length legend-tapes))))))
```

The game becomes its own museum.")
